---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="Learn how The Number Garden approaches mathematics, who it is for, and what shapes the studio."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>A place where mathematics feels alive.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The Number Garden is a warm, inquiry-driven math studio in Portland
        where children can encounter challenge, beauty, play, and belonging in
        one shared mathematical culture.
      </p>
    </div>

    <aside class="hero-card" aria-label="What shapes The Number Garden">
      <p class="card-label">What shapes the studio</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Play, patterns, conjectures, and explanation</li>
        <li>Rich mathematics with thoughtful pacing</li>
        <li>Challenge and support held together</li>
        <li>A wider entrance into mathematical thinking</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">How Learning Works</p>
      <h2>Children learn by doing mathematics.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      At The Number Garden, the goal is not to push children through a sequence
      of explanations and exercises as quickly as possible. The goal is to
      create conditions in which real thinking can happen: noticing,
      wondering, conjecturing, testing, discussing, and trying again.
    </p>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      That means learning here is built around rich mathematical tasks rather
      than worksheet speed. It means warmth and rigor belong together. It means
      children with different histories and starting points can enter the same
      mathematical culture with dignity.
    </p>

    <div class="card-grid" aria-label="How learning works at The Number Garden">
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Learning by doing</h3>
        <p>
          Children learn by engaging directly with ideas, patterns, and
          problems worth thinking about.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Rich mathematical tasks</h3>
        <p>
          The work is designed to invite noticing, conjecturing, explanation,
          and delight rather than passive compliance.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Warmth with rigor</h3>
        <p>
          Serious mathematical thinking does not require pressure, humiliation,
          or hurry.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Room to enter</h3>
        <p>
          The culture is meant to welcome many tempos and starting points
          without collapsing into narrow tracks or labels.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-accent">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">What This Means</p>
      <h2>Different children can arrive here for different reasons.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      Some children come looking for more challenge. Some need a warmer path
      back into confidence. Some are just beginning, and their families want an
      earlier, more joyful relationship to mathematics. The aim is not to sort
      children into identities, but to offer meaningful entry points into the
      same living mathematical culture.
    </p>

    <div class="card-grid" aria-label="What The Number Garden can support">
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Deeper challenge</h3>
        <p>
          For children who are ready for richer problems and more real
          mathematical thinking than school usually offers.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Rebuilding confidence</h3>
        <p>
          For children who need steadier support, stronger foundations, and a
          more dignified path back into mathematical confidence.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Early family math</h3>
        <p>
          For families who want young children to grow up with mathematics as
          part of life: playful, curious, social, and full of wonder.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light" id="pedagogy-in-action">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Pedagogy in Action</p>
      <h2>One glimpse of how this feels in practice.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      Diffy Squares is one small example of the kind of mathematical task that
      lives well here. A learner begins with four numbers at the corners of a
      square and keeps taking the differences between neighboring corners. Very
      quickly, the problem becomes full of pattern, surprise, and conjecture.
    </p>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      It has a low floor, a high ceiling, and enough structure to invite real
      thought without forcing every learner down the same path.
    </p>

    <div class="card-grid" aria-label="What Diffy Squares reveals about the pedagogy">
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Notice and wonder</h3>
        <p>Children begin by observing what changes, what repeats, and what surprises them.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Conjecture and test</h3>
        <p>Patterns lead naturally to guesses, experiments, and sharper questions.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Explain and revise</h3>
        <p>Understanding deepens as learners articulate what they think is happening and why.</p>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="inline-links">
      <a class="card-link" href="/about/diffy-squares/">
        Try the full Diffy Squares experience
      </a>
      <a class="card-link" href="/family-visit/">
        Book a family visit
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light" id="meet-paul">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Meet Paul</p>
      <h2>The person behind The Number Garden.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      The Number Garden grows out of a lifelong love of puzzles, games, and
      mathematical thinking, and out of a conviction that children deserve
      access to the real pleasures of mathematics much earlier than they
      usually get.
    </p>

    <div class="content-stack">
      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Rigorous play from the beginning</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          I grew up in a household rich with rigorous play: chess, cards,
          puzzles, games, and serious problem solving for the joy of it. That
          kind of play shaped my attention, curiosity, and sense that hard
          thinking could also be deeply pleasurable.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Why this studio exists</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          As I got older, I experienced the gap between advancement and real
          enrichment. I could move ahead in school math, but that was not the
          same thing as encountering mathematics as a living, playful,
          creative discipline.
        </p>
        <p class="section-copy">
          When I later encountered mathematics the way mathematicians actually
          do it, through definitions, conjectures, examples, and proofs, it
          felt electric. The Number Garden grows out of the belief that this
          kind of mathematical life should not be reserved for a tiny group of
          older students.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>The traditions behind the work</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          This studio is shaped by the work of Math for Love, Don Finkel, Paul
          Lockhart, Vi Hart, James Tanton, Peter Liljedahl, and others who have
          helped keep mathematics playful, serious, and socially alive.
        </p>
        <p class="section-copy">
          Their influence matters here not as branding, but as part of a real
          pedagogical lineage: one that treats children as capable thinkers and
          mathematics as something beautiful, human, and worth lingering over.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-accent contact-panel">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Next Step</p>
      <h2>Come see whether it feels right in person.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button button-primary button-large" href="/family-visit/">
        Book a family visit
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
